The cabinet shall annually on July 1 of each year report to the Governor, the Legislative Research Commission, and the Kentucky State Corrections Commission on:
The placement of prisoners within the Commonwealth's correctional system by institution, whether imprisoned in a state prison or other institution, including county jails, on probation, paroled, housed in halfway houses, sentenced to community service or otherwise;
Numbers of prisoners by type of offense;
Numbers of prisoners by number and type of prior convictions;
Numbers of prisoners paroled by type of offense and by length of time served;
Numbers of prisoners released through shock probation by type of offense and by length of time served;
Numbers of prisoners serving their full sentence by type of offense;
The percentage of felony offenders on parole or some form of post-release supervision who are participating or completing treatment consistent with assessment results, in prison and in the community;
The percentage of felony offenders whose reassessment results demonstrate reductions in criminal risk factors;
The percentage of programs that demonstrate their effectiveness in reducing recidivism;
The percentage of felony offenders on parole or some form of post-release supervision, by supervision type, who:
Are employed or in school within thirty (30) days, six (6) months, and one (1) year of the start of supervision;
Have had part-time employment for a minimum of six (6) months, and the percentage of offenders who have had full-time employment for a minimum of six (6) months;
Have housing upon release from incarceration;
Had stable housing for at least six (6) months; and
Are arrested, convicted, or incarcerated within six (6) months, one (1) year, and three (3) years;
The percentage of admissions to prison by offenders under supervision at the time of admission, including information regarding whether the violations were criminal or technical; and
Any other data that provides information on state-funded crime reduction and recidivism reduction efforts, including caseload sizes by risk level, participation in treatment and intervention programming, public safety outcomes, and cost effectiveness.
